Turkey is widening diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, the European powers were anxious to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps in Asia, is one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-renaissance style.
This is at least what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking to the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the ceiling at a time, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the westernmost passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retard to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this railroad running in Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Its isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the cold war, has passed
British and dominant forces marched out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 a ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then he has been slowly disbanding, largely overtaken by history.
But today, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's increasingly large diplomatic horizons.
The ruling party of Justice and Development - the AKP - has created an entire new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the cold war, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
Significantly, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, Turkish deputy Suat Kinikioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a run to stilts along the tracks that produced the cadences from the ancient world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intended to turn away from its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspects in the West, more notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built malls and power pastry shops, where managers in full business - both men and women - meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kinikioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
"The purpose of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbours.
The cold war was an anomaly," she tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today you have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't the case with one or the other.
They must be both.
"But surely at some point, "I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want where to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has recited in memory: the links of not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are of benefit to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can metaphorically travel those railway lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Again at Hydarpasha station, after another night in white, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's Middle East ambitions can now be largely in the hands of Turkey.
And while I wait at the ferry terminal that brings me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
Then at least there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent to advance on this fascinating country.
