The "pea car" to avoid collisions
In the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired this time by nature, and in particular by bees.
Japanese society has created a robot that, taking for example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and the Development of Brand Management, BR23C is an extension of the Security Shield to four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the home manufacturer's vehicles.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space which is very similar to the Nissan's safety shield.
But the most important thing is the composite eyes of the bees, able to see in all directions with an angle greater than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers have developed what they have defined as a Laser Range Finder.
This mechanism identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C for a radius within two metres and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to a microprocessor on board that immediately prevents collision.
"At the moment that it detects an obstacle, the small robot imitates the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at the right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, nor even diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and in the direction in which it can rotate its wheels and not exploit infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device just needs to process the information every few seconds, and act on the basis of this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers predicted, so it can work without interruptions and with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, not even megabytes."
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to the destination avoiding the obstacles present in the route.
