Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was in difficulty for the first time in Europe because of the American credit market crisis, through partial nationalisation: the three nations will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the financial institution - insurance with interests also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level on the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been under discussion for more than a year is that of Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can be a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' actions had started with a vertical collapse, serious signs of the institution's crisis were then presented in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
Bank shares fell by almost 12% on Friday, the lowest point for 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Considering the current stock prices the entire capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the bank's managers this value is not real.
The business summit blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the extra-European market due to the US plan's acceptance of $700 billion.
Monday the title slowly resumed to rise.
On Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed the new managing director of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has presented themselves with a worthy offer.
The Belgian Government had previously assured that investors should not be afraid of losing their money.
Among the bank's clients there was no panic, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary Fortis owns autonomous branches and has also purchased leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
In America life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchasing data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program whereby the use of drug prescription data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick the author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance fee and the amount due in case of health claims of the prospective customer and if they consider the risk to be too high they shall not make the insurance conditional.
A long time ago, the client had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the examination had been completed.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer's identification code you can easily have information from the pharmacies about which medicines you have purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program emerges from which diseases you suffer and in what health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is in practice unreasonably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
On the other hand, some medicines can be used for several purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraine or heat flushes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance point of view - commercial, applies as a factor of increase risk, the first two are not.
For the request and processing of data they have formed separate societies and these, before obtaining from the pharmacies the necessary information, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some firms have also recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to the medical intake data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the patient's state of health.
More and more companies have access to data and parallel control of use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control powers to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the other data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So in the end the chickens are entrusted to the mercy of the fox.
